# DevSpirits – Project Rules & Best Practices

## 1. Project Context & Goals

**DevSpirits** is a landing/SEO/geo page designed to generate leads for freelance developer projects.

- **Primary goal**: Convert visitors into leads (contact form, CTA, bookings)
- **Secondary goals**: SEO visibility, geo-targeted content, trust signals (portfolio, testimonials, skills)
- **Tech stack**: Next.js 16, React 19, TypeScript (strict), Tailwind CSS v4
- **Path aliases**: `@/*` maps to `./*` (project root)

## 1.1. Brand Compliance (CRITICAL)

- **Source of truth:** `docs/brand-brife-en.md`
- **Cursor rule:** `.cursor/rules/brand-brief.mdc` — ALERT when content, copy, CTAs, or design deviate from the brand brief
- All user-facing content must align with DevSpirits & IdanLevianDeveloper voice, messaging, and conversion structure

## 2. SEO Best Practices (CRITICAL)

**Metadata & Semantics:**

- Use `generateMetadata` in Server Components for dynamic SEO per page
- Every page must have unique `title`, `description`, and `keywords`
- Use semantic HTML: `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<header>`, `<footer>`
- Add `lang` on `<html>` (e.g. `lang="en"` or locale-specific)

**Structured Data:**

- Add JSON-LD for `Person` or `ProfessionalService` where relevant
- Add `Organization` schema for brand/contact info
- Use `WebPage` for landing pages when appropriate

**Technical SEO:**

- Use Next.js `Link` for internal navigation (no `href="#"` for CTAs)
- Ensure fast Core Web Vitals (LCP, FID, CLS)
- Use `next/image` for all images with proper `alt` and `width`/`height`
- Prefer static generation where possible: `generateStaticParams`, `generateMetadata`

**Geo-Targeting:**

- Support geo-specific content when relevant (e.g. city/region pages)
- Use `hreflang` for multi-language/geo variants
- Consider geo-specific meta descriptions and titles

## 3. Landing Page & Lead Conversion

**Conversion-Focused Design:**

- Clear CTAs above the fold (e.g. "Get a Quote", "Contact", "Book a Call")
- Minimal friction: short forms, clear value proposition
- Trust signals: testimonials, portfolio, skills, certifications
- Mobile-first: forms and CTAs must work well on small screens

**Content Structure:**

- Hero: headline + subheadline + primary CTA
- Value proposition: what you offer, why it matters
- Social proof: testimonials, logos, case studies
- Call-to-action: repeated at logical points
- Contact: form or clear contact method

**Performance:**

- Avoid heavy client-side JS above the fold
- Use Server Components for static content
- Lazy load below-the-fold content when needed

## 4. TypeScript & Strict Mode

- Use `strict: true` in tsconfig.json
- Prefer `interface` for props and object shapes
- Use `type` for unions, intersections, and computed types
- Avoid `any`; use `unknown` and narrow with type guards
- Use `import type` for type-only imports
- Use `satisfies` for config objects when appropriate

## 5. React 19 & Next.js 16 App Router

**Server vs Client Components:**

- Default to Server Components (no bundle cost)
- Use `'use client'` only when needed: interactivity, hooks, browser APIs
- Keep client boundaries as deep as possible in the tree
- Use Server Components for: data fetching, metadata, SEO

**Component Patterns:**

- Use functional components only
- Keep components small and focused
- Use composition over prop drilling

**Next.js:**

- Use `Link` for internal navigation (never `<a>` for internal routes)
- Use `next/image` for images
- Use `generateMetadata` for SEO
- Use Server Actions for form submissions when possible

## 6. Tailwind CSS v4

**Semantic Tokens:**

- Prefer semantic tokens when defined (e.g. `bg-card`, `text-foreground`)
- Use `globals.css` for design tokens; avoid raw color values

**Responsive Design:**

- Mobile-first: base styles, then `md:`, `lg:`, `xl:`
- Test layouts on multiple breakpoints

**Utilities:**

- Use standard utilities over arbitrary values when possible
- Group related utilities logically

## 7. File Organization

**Structure:**

- `app/` – Next.js App Router pages and layouts
- `components/` – reusable UI components
- `lib/` or `utils/` – utilities and helpers
- `types/` – shared TypeScript types
- `public/` – static assets (images, favicons)

**Naming:**

- Components: `ComponentName.tsx` (PascalCase)
- Utilities: `utilityName.ts` (camelCase)
- Use barrel exports (`index.ts`) for cleaner imports

## 8. Asset Organization

- Assets in `public/` with descriptive, kebab-case names
- Naming: `descriptive-purpose.format` (e.g. `hero-developer.png`)
- Avoid generic names (e.g. `image-1.png`)
- Check for existing assets before adding new ones

## 9. Code Quality & Linting

**ESLint:**

- Run `yarn lint` or `npm run lint` before committing
- Fix all ESLint errors and warnings
- No `console.log` in production code
- No commented-out code

**Prettier:**

- Single quotes
- 2 spaces indentation
- Trailing commas

## 10. Common Mistakes to Avoid

**SEO & Conversion:**

- Don’t skip or duplicate metadata across pages
- Don’t hide or obscure CTAs
- Don’t use placeholder images without `alt` text

**React/Next.js:**

- Don’t use Client Components when Server Components suffice
- Don’t use `<a>` for internal navigation
- Don’t forget `alt` on images

**Accessibility:**

- Include `alt` text on images (empty `alt=""` only for decorative images)
- Use semantic HTML
- Ensure keyboard navigation and focus states

## 11. MCP Usage

**Preferred MCPs:**

- **Context7 MCP**: Library docs, framework best practices, code examples
- **Figma Desktop MCP**: Design implementation, design tokens

**Workflow:**

- Use Context7 for React, Next.js, TypeScript, Tailwind docs
- Use Figma MCP when implementing from designs
- Prefer MCPs over web search when available

## 12. Before Committing Checklist

- [ ] `yarn lint` passes with no errors/warnings
- [ ] `npx tsc --noEmit` passes
- [ ] Metadata is correct for changed pages
- [ ] All images have `alt` text
- [ ] CTAs and forms work as expected
- [ ] Responsive layout tested on mobile/desktop
